Fig. 1.2 The ‚Äúseven liberal arts,‚Äù with Grammatica and Rhetorica on the top and top-right (from: Herrad of Landsberg, ‚ÄúHortus deliciarum‚Äù [1180])

For a long time, the foreign languages which were studied and taught most were Latin, Greek and Hebrew, the three ‚Äúsacred‚Äù languages of the Bible. From the 16th and 17th centuries onwards more and more of the modern European languages started developing coherent traditions of producing teaching and refer-

