On the strength of such evidence, can we put forward the claim that mega is now an adjective and adverb in English? The answer to this question is a guarded yes, and much rests on the careful interpretation of the examples. For instance, there is no reason to consider forms such as ‚Äúmega brewers‚Äù (1) or ‚Äúmega popular‚Äù (6) as particularly innovative. They could easily be respelled as mega-brewers or mega-popular. Note, though, that sometimes it would be possible to add material in between mega and the following word: the mega commercial brewers, a mega and utterly exhausting portage, and this is only possible on the assumption that mega has been reanalysed (cf. p. 68) as an adjective. In our list, there is at least one clear example which shows that such a reanalysis is possible: ‚Äúthink mega‚Äù (example 16).
As usual in corpus-based work, finding the answer to our initial question leads to the formulation of new ones. How common, for example, are combinations such as ‚Äúmega and,‚Äù ‚Äúreally mega‚Äù or ‚Äúrather mega,‚Äù in which mega may or must be an adjective?
